success.question_text: In what the direction will the ship now be travelling?

review_4.column_1_text:
The ship is now travelling in a south-easterly direction.

Tip

A compass rose shows directions to North, East, South and West. In between these directions are North-East, South-East, South-West and North-West.

success.question_text:
Each edge of the cube used a 10-cm length of wire.

What was the total length of wire Carl used to make the cube?

stimulus_1.text: Carl made a cube using a length of wire.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A solid can be described by its number of faces, edges and vertices.

success.question_text:
I am a 3-D shape. My net has two circular surfaces and one rectangular face.

What am I?

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Make sure you can identify the different solids from their nets.

success.question_text: What is the shape of the cross-section?

stimulus_1.text:
A cone is cut with a knife.

The cut is at right angles to the base of the cone as shown in the diagram.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A cross-section is the slice formed when a solid is cut.

success.question_text: Which of these is the top view of Feng’s solid?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a solid is built from a number of cubes it can be viewed from a number of directions. These views from different directions may not be the same. Sometimes cubes cannot be seen because they are blocked by others.

success.question_text: What is the view from the back?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a solid is built from a number of identical cubes it can be viewed from a number of directions. These views from different directions may not be the same. Sometimes cubes cannot be seen because they are blocked by others.

success.question_text: What fraction of the cubes have more than two faces painted?

stimulus_1.text: A solid was made up of 36 small cubes.

stimulus_3.text:
All of the six faces of the solid were painted.

After the paint was dry, the solid was pulled apart into the 36 small cubes.

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

If a solid is formed using small cubes it may need to be dismantled to solve a problem.

success.question_text: Through how many degrees has the rotation occurred?

stimulus_2.text: The shape on the left has been rotated in a clockwise direction to form the shape on the right.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When rotating an object, pretend that it is placed on a clock-face. Next, identify a feature and watch it rotate around the clock-face. Suppose it was the 6 on a clock-face—a quarter-turn to the right (or clockwise) means that it is now at the 9.

success.question_text: What could be the view of the solid from the front?

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows the view from the top of a solid:

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Viewed from the top, the edges of a solid appear as lines and any vertex of the solid (as in the top of a pyramid) will appear as a point.

success.question_text: How many rectangles the size of Rectangle G will fit on the piece of paper?

stimulus_1.text: A rectangular piece of paper is divided into smaller and smaller rectangles. Rectangle A is half the size of the original rectangle. Rectangle B is half the size of Rectangle A. Rectangle C is half the size of Rectangle B and so on.

review_3.column_1_text:
Two of Rectangle G will fit in Rectangle F. So four of Rectangle G will fit in Rectangle E.

Two of Rectangle E will fit in Rectangle D so eight of Rectangle G will fit in Rectangle D.

Two of Rectangle D will fit in Rectangle C so 16 of Rectangle G will fit in Rectangle C.

Two of Rectangle C will fit in Rectangle B so 32 of Rectangle G will fit in Rectangle B.

Two of Rectangle B will fit in Rectangle A so 64 of Rectangle G will fit in Rectangle A.

review_4.column_1_text:
Two of Rectangle A will fit on the whole sheet so 128 of Rectangle G will fit on the sheet of paper.

128 rectangles the size of Rectangle G will fit on the piece of paper.

Tip

Think carefully and take time to answer a question.

success.question_text: Through how many degrees could this shape be rotated in a clockwise direction so that it looks exactly the same?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Clockwise is the direction in which the hands of a clock move. Anticlockwise is the opposite direction to that in which the hands of a clock move.

success.question_text: What did her paper look like before she unfolded it?

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When paper folding, the number of layers of paper gives the number of repeated cut-out shapes.

success.question_text: This solid is made up of a number of small cubes. How many of those small cubes are there?

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

When a solid is made from small cubes many will be hidden from view. Remember to count all cubes, visible or hidden.

success.question_text: How much further is it to walk from the Food Hall to Q passing I and L on the way, than by the shortest route?

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows a map of a showground and the position of many of the exhibition buildings.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Sometimes a little thought can make a question easier. For example, in this question both routes have distances of 100 m, 250 m and 150 m. The difference is the 500 m from the Food Hall to Building I.

success.question_text: If they walk at the same speed to and from their buildings and do arrive back at the same time, which girl will spend the least amount of time at her exhibit?

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows a map of a showground and the position of many of the exhibition buildings.

stimulus_3.text: Four friends, Olivia, Chloe, Sienna and Amy, are at the Food Hall. They decide to each set off at the same time to visit a different exhibit and meet back at the Food Hall at the same time. Olivia is going to building A, Chloe to building K, Sienna to building S and Amy to P. They each travel the shortest route to and from the buildings.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

If you don’t know that a map is drawn to scale, you cannot judge distances by just looking at them.

success.question_text: What does his card look like now?

stimulus_1.text: Karl is playing with a card. He flips it over the right side edge so that it is face down and then flips it over the bottom edge so that it is face up again.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

A flip is another name for a reflection. The line of reflection is like an axis of symmetry.

success.question_text: The actual distance from P to Q is

stimulus_2.text: Each square on this map is 1 square centimetre. Each centimetre on the map represents an actual distance of 4 kilometres.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

A scale must be the same for the whole map.

success.question_text: The actual distance from T to R is about

stimulus_2.text: Each square on this map is 1 square centimetre. Each centimetre on the map represents an actual distance of 4 kilometres. The length on the map from P to U is 5 centimetres.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

A scale must be the same for the whole map.

success.question_text: Which is the net of the cube?

stimulus_1.text: Here are two views of the same cube:

review_3.column_1_text:
The face opposite the blue face cannot be seen in either view of the cube. It must be the white face.

The orange and green faces must be opposite the yellow and grey faces in some order. If the orange face is opposite the yellow face it would be on the bottom of the first view of the cube. If the cube in the second view is rolled over its bottom front edge so that orange is on the bottom and yellow at the top, the right side would be green, but on the cube in the first view you can see that it is grey.

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

Practise drawing, cutting out and folding nets.

success.question_text: Which of these sizes represents the size of the angle between the hands of a clock at 10 o’clock?
